		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />For volume envelopes and arpeggio envelopes (basically like pitch envelopes), I actually keep my "ticks" system. Seriously, 1 tick is usually super fast (many times 1/40 of a second). I use software envelopes ONLY. If you plan on adjusting the speed of a song and its volume envelope speed, do not use hardware decay. Anyways, an "instrument" that will play a pitch fading out would use a volume envelope that looks like:
<br />
<br />VolumeEnvelope:
<br /> .db $08,$08,$08,$08,$07,$07,$06,$06,$05,$05,$04,$04,$03,$03,$02,$02,$01,$01,$01,$00
<br />
<br />Where each entry is a volume for the square wave. Each "tick" it moves onto the next entry.
<br />
<br />Seriously though, like I was saying before, I would stay away from hardware volume decay. Manually update the volume. It may seem like it'd be "blocky", but it's not at all. It goes too fast for you to notice.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
